ing Language to Palladio Component Model}},\n  year = {2015},\n  month = {November},\n  day = {6},\n  booktitle = {Proceedings of the 2015 Symposium on Software Performance (SSP)},\n  location = {Munich, Germany},\n  abstract = {Model-based performance predictions and reconfigurations enable optimizing resource efficiency while ensuring that Quality-of-Service demands are met in today\'s complex ITsystems. The Descartes Modeling Language (DML) and the Palladio Component Model (PCM) are two architectural performance modeling formalisms applied in this context. This paper compares DML to PCM concerning similarities, differences and semantic gaps. Based on this, we propose a mapping from DML to PCM for which we implemented a tool realizing an automated transformation.},\n  pdf = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/905.pdf},\n  slides = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/905},\n}\n\n','J&#252;rgen Walter, , Simon Eismann, , and Adrian Hildebrandt, .\nAutomated Transformation of Descartes Modeling Language to Palladio Component Model.\nIn <span class=\"em\"> Proceedings of the 2015 Symposium on Software Performance (SSP)</span>, Munich, Germany, November 6, 2015.\n[&nbsp;<a class=\"bib-preview-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'bib-of-WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM\')\">bib</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a class=\"abstract-preview-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'abstract-of-WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM\')\">Abstract</a>\n&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/905.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">pdf</a>\n&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/905\" target=\"_blank\">slides</a>\n&nbsp;]\n<div id=\"bib-of-WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM\" class=\"inline-bib\" style=\"display:none;\"><pre>@inproceedings{WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM,\n  author = {J\\\"{u}rgen Walter and Simon Eismann and Adrian Hildebrandt},\n  title = {{Automated Transformation of Descartes Modeling Language to Palladio Component Model}},\n  year = {2015},\n  month = {November},\n  day = {6},\n  booktitle = {Proceedings of the 2015 Symposium on Software Performance (SSP)},\n  location = {Munich, Germany},\n  abstract = {Model-based performance predictions and reconfigurations enable optimizing resource efficiency while ensuring that Quality-of-Service demands are met in today\'s complex ITsystems. The Descartes Modeling Language (DML) and the Palladio Component Model (PCM) are two architectural performance modeling formalisms applied in this context. This paper compares DML to PCM concerning similarities, differences and semantic gaps. Based on this, we propose a mapping from DML to PCM for which we implemented a tool realizing an automated transformation.},\n  pdf = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/905.pdf},\n  slides = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/905},\n}\n\n</pre></div>\n<div id=\"abstract-of-WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM\" class=\"inline-bib\" style=\"display:none;\"><blockquote>Model-based performance predictions and reconfigurations enable optimizing resource efficiency while ensuring that Quality-of-Service demands are met in today\'s complex ITsystems. The Descartes Modeling Language (DML) and the Palladio Component Model (PCM) are two architectural performance modeling formalisms applied in this context. This paper compares DML to PCM concerning similarities, differences and semantic gaps. Based on this, we propose a mapping from DML to PCM for which we implemented a tool realizing an automated transformation.</blockquote></div>','<a name=\"WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM\"></a><pre>\n@inproceedings{WaEiHi2015-SPP-DML2PCM,\n  author = {J\\\"{u}rgen Walter and Simon Eismann and Adrian Hildebrandt},\n  title = {{Automated Transformation of Descartes Modeling Language to Palladio Component Model}},\n  year = {2015},\n  month = {November},\n  day = {6},\n  booktitle = {Proceedings of the 2015 Symposium on Software Performance (SSP)},\n  location = {Munich, Germany},\n  abstract = {Model-based performance predictions and reconfigurations enable optimizing resource efficiency while ensuring that Quality-of-Service demands are met in today\'s complex ITsystems. The Descartes Modeling Language (DML) and the Palladio Component Model (PCM) are two architectural performance modeling formalisms applied in this context. This paper compares DML to PCM concerning similarities, differences and semantic gaps. Based on this, we propose a mapping from DML to PCM for which we implemented a tool realizing an automated transformation.},\n  pdf = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/905.pdf\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/905.pdf</a>},\n  slides = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/905\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/905</a>}\n}\n</pre>\n\n','Model-based performance predictions and reconfigurations enable optimizing resource efficiency while ensuring that Quality-of-Service demands are met in today\'s complex ITsystems. The Descartes Modeling Language (DML) and the Palladio Component Model (PCM) are two architectural performance modeling formalisms applied in this context. This paper compares DML to PCM concerning similarities, differences and semantic gaps. Based on this, we propose a mapping from DML to PCM for which we implemented a tool realizing an automated transformation.','{Automated Transformation of Descartes Modeling Language to Palladio Component Model}',0,11,2015,11,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-10-12 07:21:08','2017-01-24 21:18:02',0),(906,'paper','KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS','inproceedings','@inproceedings{KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS,\n  author = {J\\\'{o}akim von Kistowski and Samuel Kounev},\n  abstract = {{Performance and power scale non-linearly with device utilization, making characterization and prediction of energy efficiency at a given load level a challenging issue. A common approach to address this problem is the creation of power or performance state tables for a pre-measured subset of all possible system states. Approaches to determine performance and power for a state not included in the measured subset use simple interpolation, such as nearest neighbor interpolation, or define state switching rules. This leads to a loss in accuracy, as unmeasured system states are not considered. In this paper, we compare different interpolation functions and automatically configure and select functions for a given domain or measurement set. We evaluate our approach by comparing interpolation of measurement data subsets against power and performance measurements on a commodity server. We show that for non-extrapolating models interpolation is significantly more accurate than regression, with our automatically configured interpolation function improving modeling accuracy up to 43.6\\%.}},\n  title = {{Univariate Interpolation-based Modeling of Power and Performance}},\n  year = {2015},\n  booktitle = {Proceedings of the 9th EAI International Conference on Performance Evaluation Methodologies and Tools (VALUETOOLS 2015)},\n  location = {Berlin, Germany},\n  month = {December},\n  day = {14--16},\n  keywords = {Interpolation, Energy Efficiency, Power, Performance, Interpolation, Utilization, SERT},\n  slides = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/906},\n  pdf = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/906.pdf},\n  doi = {http://dx.doi.org/10.4108/eai.14-12-2015.2262579},\n}\n\n','J&#243;akim von Kistowski,  and Samuel Kounev, .\nUnivariate Interpolation-based Modeling of Power and Performance.\nIn <span class=\"em\"> Proceedings of the 9th EAI International Conference on Performance Evaluation Methodologies and Tools (VALUETOOLS 2015)</span>, Berlin, Germany, December 14&ndash;16, 2015.\n[&nbsp;<a class=\"bib-preview-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'bib-of-KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS\')\">bib</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a class=\"abstract-preview-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'abstract-of-KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS\')\">Abstract</a>\n&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/906.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">pdf</a>\n&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/906\" target=\"_blank\">slides</a>\n&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/http://dx.doi.org/10.4108/eai.14-12-2015.2262579\" target=\"_blank\">DOI</a>\n&nbsp;]\n<div id=\"bib-of-KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS\" class=\"inline-bib\" style=\"display:none;\"><pre>@inproceedings{KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS,\n  author = {J\\\'{o}akim von Kistowski and Samuel Kounev},\n  abstract = {{Performance and power scale non-linearly with device utilization, making characterization and prediction of energy efficiency at a given load level a challenging issue. A common approach to address this problem is the creation of power or performance state tables for a pre-measured subset of all possible system states. Approaches to determine performance and power for a state not included in the measured subset use simple interpolation, such as nearest neighbor interpolation, or define state switching rules. This leads to a loss in accuracy, as unmeasured system states are not considered. In this paper, we compare different interpolation functions and automatically configure and select functions for a given domain or measurement set. We evaluate our approach by comparing interpolation of measurement data subsets against power and performance measurements on a commodity server. We show that for non-extrapolating models interpolation is significantly more accurate than regression, with our automatically configured interpolation function improving modeling accuracy up to 43.6\\%.}},\n  title = {{Univariate Interpolation-based Modeling of Power and Performance}},\n  year = {2015},\n  booktitle = {Proceedings of the 9th EAI International Conference on Performance Evaluation Methodologies and Tools (VALUETOOLS 2015)},\n  location = {Berlin, Germany},\n  month = {December},\n  day = {14--16},\n  keywords = {Interpolation, Energy Efficiency, Power, Performance, Interpolation, Utilization, SERT},\n  slides = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/906},\n  pdf = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/906.pdf},\n  doi = {http://dx.doi.org/10.4108/eai.14-12-2015.2262579},\n}\n\n</pre></div>\n<div id=\"abstract-of-KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS\" class=\"inline-bib\" style=\"display:none;\"><blockquote>{Performance and power scale non-linearly with device utilization, making characterization and prediction of energy efficiency at a given load level a challenging issue. A common approach to address this problem is the creation of power or performance state tables for a pre-measured subset of all possible system states. Approaches to determine performance and power for a state not included in the measured subset use simple interpolation, such as nearest neighbor interpolation, or define state switching rules. This leads to a loss in accuracy, as unmeasured system states are not considered. In this paper, we compare different interpolation functions and automatically configure and select functions for a given domain or measurement set. We evaluate our approach by comparing interpolation of measurement data subsets against power and performance measurements on a commodity server. We show that for non-extrapolating models interpolation is significantly more accurate than regression, with our automatically configured interpolation function improving modeling accuracy up to 43.6\\%.}</blockquote></div>','<a name=\"KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS\"></a><pre>\n@inproceedings{KiKo2015-VALUETOOLS,\n  author = {J\\\'{o}akim von Kistowski and Samuel Kounev},\n  abstract = {{Performance and power scale non-linearly with device utilization, making characterization and prediction of energy efficiency at a given load level a challenging issue. A common approach to address this problem is the creation of power or performance state tables for a pre-measured subset of all possible system states. Approaches to determine performance and power for a state not included in the measured subset use simple interpolation, such as nearest neighbor interpolation, or define state switching rules. This leads to a loss in accuracy, as unmeasured system states are not considered. In this paper, we compare different interpolation functions and automatically configure and select functions for a given domain or measurement set. We evaluate our approach by comparing interpolation of measurement data subsets against power and performance measurements on a commodity server. We show that for non-extrapolating models interpolation is significantly more accurate than regression, with our automatically configured interpolation function improving modeling accuracy up to 43.6\\%.}},\n  title = {{Univariate Interpolation-based Modeling of Power and Performance}},\n  year = {2015},\n  booktitle = {Proceedings of the 9th EAI International Conference on Performance Evaluation Methodologies and Tools (VALUETOOLS 2015)},\n  location = {Berlin, Germany},\n  month = {December},\n  day = {14--16},\n  keywords = {Interpolation, Energy Efficiency, Power, Performance, Interpolation, Utilization, SERT},\n  slides = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/906\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/906</a>},\n  pdf = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/906.pdf\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/906.pdf</a>},\n  doi = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.4108/eai.14-12-2015.2262579\">http://dx.doi.org/10.4108/eai.14-12-2015.2262579</a>}\n}\n</pre>\n\n','{Performance and power scale non-linearly with device utilization, making characterization and prediction of energy efficiency at a given load level a challenging issue. A common approach to address this problem is the creation of power or performance state tables for a pre-measured subset of all possible system states. Approaches to determine performance and power for a state not included in the measured subset use simple interpolation, such as nearest neighbor interpolation, or define state switching rules. This leads to a loss in accuracy, as unmeasured system states are not considered. In this paper, we compare different interpolation functions and automatically configure and select functions for a given domain or measurement set. We evaluate our approach by comparing interpolation of measurement data subsets against power and performance measurements on a commodity server. We show that for non-extrapolating models interpolation is significantly more accurate than regression, with our automatically configured interpolation function improving modeling accuracy up to 43.6\\%.}','{Univariate Interpolation-based Modeling of Power and Performance}',0,12,2015,12,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-11-03 10:31:17','2017-01-24 21:18:02',0),(907,'talk','talk-Kistowski-SSP15','misc','@misc{talk-Kistowski-SSP15,\n  author = {J\\\'{o}akim von Kistowski},\n  title = {{Common Errors and Assumptions in Energy Measurement and Management}},\n  howpublished = {Technical Talk at Symposium on Software Performance (SSP) 2015},\n  days = {5--6},\n  month = {November},\n  year = {2015},\n  slides = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/slides/907},\n}\n\n','J&#243;akim von Kistowski, .\nCommon Errors and Assumptions in Energy Measurement and Management.\nTechnical Talk at Symposium on Software Performance (SSP) 2015, November 2015.\n[&nbsp;<a class=\"bib-preview-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'bib-of-talk-Kistowski-SSP15\')\">bib</